snippet.textDisplay:
I think hospital ships are a brilliant idea. My country Sweden should also have one ship in north, and one in south, and in east and west. So if thousands of hospital beds in one city is needed, then you only need to move a ship to the city where it is needed if a disaster struck. It can also be used in humanitarian missions in peace time or help friendly nations when they get earth quakes or other disasters. This would be a great add-on to the capacity to treat patients when there are no hospital rooms left in a town.
And you can have top notch quality equipment ready when you need it.
Hopefully will these ships prove their value now when New York is in a crisis.

snippet.textDisplay: The UK has a primary casualty receiving ship called RFA(Royal Fleet Auxiliary) Argus. It differs from a hospital ship as it is armed with self defense weapons and ammunition. It is also not painted white with red crosses. It has 70 general ward beds, 20 high dependency beds and 10 intensive care beds. It also has a large landing pad for 3 medium sized helicopters and a hangar below decks that can hold 4 helicopters at once. The ship is also an aviation training ship so it use to carry BAE Sea harriers FA2s which can be used in a ground attack role or for Air superiority.
